english:
  title: Colophon on Jungo's Collection of Farewell Poems Upon His Return from Studies
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Jungo was the grandson of Master Muk-heon and the second son of the Two Ministers. In his twenties, he entered the Middle Kingdom and was appointed as a student of the National Academy, where he studied diligently for a long time and earned the praise of his peers. When he requested leave to return home to visit his parents, the great scholars of the age all gifted him parting poems, and this became a matter of honor throughout the scholarly circles.

    After the calamities of the xinchoulian upheaval scattered these verses, Jung Hee recovered them and entrusted them to the Min family. Of the original collection, only nine poems remain, and even these are fragmentary and illegible, their lines broken and incomplete. I have consulted what I could hear and completed the transcription as shown above. Of Master Geup-am's poems, I obtained only a single line, yet I could not refrain from recording it, hoping perhaps that one day someone might come forward with more.

    The farewell poems presented by the great scholars are indeed preserved in their complete collections, yet few copies circulate. This particular volume scattered among the people, and rarely do descendants possess it. How much less so when its pages have become mere covering for a sealed jar, lost to time.

    Jungo's son, in his filial devotion, moved heaven itself. Thus did the Jung family come to preserve these verses. Is this not remarkable?

    Reading this collection while recovering from illness, I am moved to reflection. I too am one who studied in the land of the Middle Kingdom, yet I never received even a single line of encouragement from my seniors. Beholding this volume, I find myself admiring Jungo all the more. Truly, Jungo may be said to have had a worthy son. Had this collection been allowed to perish and fade into oblivion, how could the ink traces of our sage ancestors continue to illuminate this age and generations to come? Yes, Jungo may indeed be said to have had a worthy son.
  footnotes:
    - The 'xinchoulian upheaval' (신축년 난리) likely refers to the social upheaval or warfare during the year xinchoul (辛丑) in the Joseon period.
    - The reference to 'Two Ministers' (二相) indicates Jungo's father held an important government position.
    - The 'National Academy' (成均館) was the highest educational institution in Goryeo and Joseon Korea.
    - The 'Middle Kingdom' (中國) refers to China, where Joseon scholars often traveled for further study during this period.
